snippet.textDisplay:
Compared to severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in 2003, the novel coronavirus that broke out in China last year has spread faster and wider, affecting more than 50 countries in just two months. There have also been cases in which the incubation period extends beyond 14 days and the infected patients show no symptoms, making it harder to stem the virus' spread.

Another challenge is the lack of preventive vaccines or therapeutic drugs. Although a number of companies are working or planning to work on it, the outcome remains uncertain. Remdesivir, a new drug made by Gilead Sciences, for example, is expected to work only on mild or moderate cases. The lengthy drug approval process may also mean that even before a drug is put on the market, the quick spread and mutation of the virus may have made it beyond treatment.

Some hope that the epidemic would fade like SARS as the temperature rises, but there is no evidence yet. “We absolutely don’t know that,” says Trudie Lang at the University of Oxford. “I keep asking virologist colleagues this and nobody knows.”

Millions of people are placed under quarantine as the Chinese communist regime scrambles to contain the virus. With no end of quarantine in sight, many, especially those in Wuhan, feel trapped in their own homes, and their mental health is worrisome, which may lead to another humanitarian crisis.

As China's leaders grapple with the epidemic and its devastating impact on the economy and people's physical and psychological well-being, I am writing this open letter to share my understanding of the plague. I hope that they will learn from history and find a solution that addresses the fundamental, underlying causes of the epidemic.

snippet.textDisplay: Knitting and crochet surprinsingly fashionable and cool these days check out these cool example things you can make from Ravelry persons faves https://www.ravelry.com/people/GemsGemstone/favorites?bundles=0 , plus stuff like Hedgehog Fibres yarn, which is wearable art and has great patterns like the Outline which took me 3wks tomake using 1hr a day. Try it out for so much happys, honestly! Eco friendly wool instead of plastic toys.. making toys like Susan Claudinos cool monsters and cute bunnys.. look her up.. Its easy to Youtube learned to crochet from ppl like Happyberry ie making her bracelet, heart pattern, mandala and hanging owl? That uses acrylic (plastic wool) but is a good start :) theres pattern lists on the Scheepjes list of bloggers, like a fun rainbow tablet case.. blankets in any bright colours you want as display pieces too or weird foody designs from ppl like Twinkie-chans crochet too or Attic24 s blankets are grea . Plus the yarns are so cool these days, knitting using half as much yarn as it makes a less thick material so you can afford great yarns like QingFibre, Homespun House, Madelinetosh.. its squishy and soft and like wearing a a marshmallowey cloud.. and the kidsilk yarns..wow..the texture. Its great to make a pattern like Stephen Wests The Doodler or his Exploration Station.. or Outline by Hedgehog Fibres or Birds of a Feather by Andrea Mowry, also Boyland knitworks. For simple homeley stuff theres Melody Hoffman or fun foresty quirky folklore stuff by tinyowlknits. Enjoy some cafe knitting with friends and enjoy real happy, colour, art, comfort with eco friendly crafts to make and share! Also look at how fun handspinning is with wool like from SpinCity batts..i love there 'Blue marble' and 'Pink Quartz' fibres and its so cute to spin with flowery drop spindles that are new and fresh..lets make it a trend! Spin it how you like then knit a chunky scarf/blanket squares, mug mats, mandala, anything ^-^ Scheepjes makes nice bright cotton yarns too.. but believe me, you havent really expereinced happy textures and comfort till youve tried a proper quality sock yarn like Hedgehog Fibres, Qing, Homespun House, Madelinetosh, Malabrigo, etc etc. Also theres cool knitting blogs by Homespun House or Kirsty Glass knits.. Be happy, be eco for the future with quality materials that are soo soft like wool, and maybe try handdying a wool type (there many types of wool, some rough, some silky, some springy..) sometime or knitting, crochet weaving etc. And see how fun and easy it is, how beautiful the batts for handspinning are...and enjoy.♡♡
